First of all, `Integer` is a `final class` meaning it does not make sense to talk about subclasses to `Integer` as there aren&#39;t any. That out of the way, there are two ways to achieve what I believe is the desired effect.

&lt;h2&gt;1. Not using generics&lt;/h2&gt; 
A list of Integers will allow you to add instances of subclasses to the Integer class (which once again do not exist). This would look something like this:

```java
public int countSpecial(Collection&lt;Integer&gt; input, Predicate&lt;Integer&gt; p) {
	int count = 0;
    for(Integer i : input) {
		if(p.test(i)) {
			count++
    	}
    }
    return count;
}
```

&lt;h2&gt;2. Not using wildcards&lt;/h2&gt; 
This will allow you to utilise the benefits of generics while still being able to achieve the desired effect - and I think this is what you were trying to do. It would look something like this:

```java
public &lt;T extends Integer&gt; int countSpecial(Collection&lt;T&gt; input, Predicate&lt;T&gt; p) {
	int count = 0;
    for(T t : input) { // t will be an instance of an Integer or an Integer subclass (which doesn&#39;t exist)
		if(p.test(i)) {
			count++
    	}
    }
    return count;
}
```

