answers.body_markdown:
The (basic) initialization order of a constructor is:

* Invoke the super constructor
* Invoke the instance initializers (and field initializers, which are just syntactic sugar for field declaration + instance initializers)
* Execute the rest of the constructor

So, for:

```
class Sub extends Super
{
    Integer data = null;
    
    Sub(int f)
    {
        super(f);
    }

    // ...
}
```

this is the same as:

```
class Sub extends Super
{
    Integer data;
    
    Sub(int f)
    {
        super(f);
        data = null;
    }

    // ...
}
```

So, if anything changes `data` in the call to `super(f)`, that is overwritten by the `data = null;`.

As mentioned by [Mark Rotteveel](https://stackoverflow.com/users/466862/mark-rotteveel), the way to avoid this is to not invoke overridable methods in constructors. This is covered in more detail in *Effective Java*, Item 19 (in the 3rd Ed - page 95 paragraph starting &quot;Constructors must not invoke overridable methods&quot;).

    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Sub sub = new Sub(10);
            sub.init();
            sub.showData();
        }
    }

